---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import Header from '../components/Header.astro'
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'
---

<Base title="Credits — Extol">
  <Header />

  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-600 text-bark-900 mb-4">When Your Community Is Ready for More</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-warm-gray-500 mb-12">You started with transparent governance. Here's what comes next.</p>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Extol meets communities where they are. Some groups just need
        visibility — who showed up, what was decided, where the money went.
        That's transparent governance, and it's powerful on its own.
      </p>
      <p>
        But some communities reach a point where visibility isn't enough.
        The people doing the work want more than a record — they want
        <strong>credit</strong>.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Credit Economy</h2>
      <p class="text-warm-gray-400 italic">Everything in transparent governance, plus contributions that count.</p>

      <p>
        Your members already show up, volunteer, vote, and do the unglamorous
        work that keeps the community running. With a credit economy, that
        work earns <strong>Credits</strong> — a running tally of contribution that belongs
        to each member.
      </p>

      <h3>What Credits do</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Splits and settlements.</strong> When your group earns revenue — merch
          sales, streaming royalties, grant disbursements, tournament
          winnings — Credits determine how it's divided. No more awkward
          conversations about who deserves what. The work is already on the
          record.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Weighted decisions.</strong> Members who've invested more in the
          community have more influence in its decisions. Not because they
          paid more — because they contributed more. Influence grows with
          contribution.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Portable history.</strong> Credits travel with the person who earned
          them. A member who's active in three communities has a contribution
          history across all three — visible to any group they join next.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>What Credits are not</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Not money. You can't buy them. They're earned.</li>
        <li>Not publicly traded. Credits live inside the Extol network.</li>
        <li>Not cryptocurrency. No wallet, no exchange, no price chart.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Think of Credits like course credits at a university — earned through
        participation, accumulated over time, and meaningful to anyone who
        understands the system.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>How a community upgrades</h2>

      <p>
        You don't apply. You don't migrate. You don't start over.
      </p>
      <p>
        When your community is ready, the coordinator initiates an upgrade
        vote. Members review what changes — primarily that contributions now
        earn Credits and that Credits carry governance weight. The community
        decides together. If the vote passes, your existing history carries
        forward. Every activity already logged, every decision already
        recorded — it all counts.
      </p>
      <p>
        No one is opted in without their knowledge. Every member gets a
        clear explanation and an individual choice.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Standing — your commitment to this community</h2>

      <p>When you earn Credits, you choose how to allocate them:</p>
      <p>
        <strong>Standing</strong> is Credits you commit to a specific community. It's
        irrevocable — your skin in the game. The more Standing you hold, the
        more your voice matters in that community's decisions. Standing says:
        <em>I'm not going anywhere.</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Liquid Credits</strong> stay flexible. Use them for settlements, carry
        them to other communities, or hold them as a record of contribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every member controls their own balance between Standing and liquid
        Credits. There's no right answer — it depends on how committed you
        are to this particular group versus the broader network.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>What comes after Credits</h2>

      <p>
        Some communities eventually want their Credits to be recognized
        beyond the Extol network — by lenders, employers, grant-makers, or
        other institutions. We're building toward that. It involves careful
        governance, member consent at every step, and infrastructure that
        doesn't exist yet.
      </p>
      <p>
        We'll share more when it's ready. For now: your Credits are yours,
        your history is verified, and the work you've done finally has a
        record that belongs to you.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Is this right for your community?</h2>

      <h3>Upgrade when:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Members regularly ask "who's putting in the most work?"</li>
        <li>Your group splits revenue or manages shared resources</li>
        <li>You want contribution history to mean something beyond this group</li>
        <li>Decisions should reflect investment, not just attendance</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Stay on transparent governance when:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Visibility and accountability are enough</li>
        <li>Your group doesn't split revenue or manage significant shared money</li>
        <li>Equal voice in decisions is the right model for your community</li>
        <li>You're a tax-exempt organization and want to keep things simple</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Both are real products. Neither is a stepping stone to the other.
        Your community can stay on transparent governance forever and get
        full value from Extol.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <p><em>Questions? <a href="mailto:hello@extol.work">Contact us</a></em></p>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-bark-900, #2C1810);
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-bark-900, #2C1810);
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .prose p, .prose li {
    color: var(--color-warm-gray-500, #6B5E54);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .prose ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    list-style-type: disc;
  }
  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .prose a {
    color: var(--color-terracotta-500, #C75B3F);
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .prose hr {
    border: none;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-warm-gray-200, #E5DDD5);
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }
  .prose strong {
    color: var(--color-bark-900, #2C1810);
  }
</style>
